WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.960
Hello, everyone. My name is Thomas. Thank you all for joining me both here live and if you're there online

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:12.720
And welcome to my talk. There's a new plumber in town now the

00:00:13.440 --> 00:00:20.400
Observant among the audience will quickly figure out that this is about the plumber package at least if you know about the plumber package

00:00:22.240 --> 00:00:24.879
Plumber has been with us for a while now

00:00:25.440 --> 00:00:31.480
It's it's a pretty old package. You may not know it, but the first commit was back in June 10th in

00:00:32.200 --> 00:00:33.799
2015 and

00:00:33.799 --> 00:00:39.880
The statisticians between you will quickly figure out that this means that plumber has a 10 year old anniversary

00:00:40.680 --> 00:00:42.680
this year, so

00:00:43.320 --> 00:00:45.480
if you if you read the

00:00:46.360 --> 00:00:50.959
Title of the slide you might get the sense that this talk will not end well for plumber

00:00:50.959 --> 00:00:52.360
um

00:00:52.360 --> 00:00:57.279
But I think we should just like take a brief moment and and recognize

00:00:57.279 --> 00:01:02.840
What a tremendous success plumber has been both as a package, but also at large for their community

00:01:02.840 --> 00:01:09.639
I mean it has allowed data scientists with no or very limited knowledge about web technologies

00:01:09.959 --> 00:01:15.919
To take their R code and share it with the world or share with their organization. I mean that is tremendous

00:01:18.440 --> 00:01:20.440
But it's an old package and

00:01:21.199 --> 00:01:28.360
I have some experience with old packages. I also maintain a package called ggplot2 which is 18 years old today, so

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:34.239
I have I know something about old code and one of the kind of you can call it a

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:41.599
Law of thermodynamics of coding is that old code accrue technical depth. There's no way around it

00:01:42.559 --> 00:01:47.480
So what do you do once your code evolves into something that becomes hard to maintain?

00:01:47.959 --> 00:01:52.239
There's different ways to do it deal with this one of them is to kind of just accept the situation

00:01:52.239 --> 00:01:57.519
There's nothing wrong with that. I mean you can just say well this code is horrible to maintain

00:01:57.519 --> 00:02:03.320
But on the other hand there's not a lot to do in it, so whenever I need to like delve into it

00:02:03.320 --> 00:02:05.800
I just have to accept that I have to fight with this code base

00:02:06.440 --> 00:02:08.440
This is this is an absolutely

00:02:09.080 --> 00:02:13.320
Acceptable approach to it because on the other hand the code base is trusted and true

00:02:13.320 --> 00:02:18.320
It has a lot of mileage under its belt, so there's nothing wrong with keeping it around you just have to kind of

00:02:18.320 --> 00:02:24.320
Reconcile yourself that it will not be a pleasant experience to to continue coding with it

00:02:24.320 --> 00:02:31.320
There's another way around it. You can try to kind of surgically replace some of the the code that that is

00:02:31.320 --> 00:02:33.320
responsible for the technical depth

00:02:33.320 --> 00:02:35.320
This is kind of what we do in ggplot2

00:02:35.320 --> 00:02:42.320
I think every every time we release ggplot2 we have taken out some of the old code and placed it with something new

00:02:42.320 --> 00:02:47.320
and this is this is perilous in terms of

00:02:47.320 --> 00:02:53.320
Maintaining a package in the sense that it's very hard to convince yourself that when you replace something internally

00:02:53.320 --> 00:02:57.320
That it just continues to work as before outside of the world

00:02:57.320 --> 00:03:01.320
So it's certainly not something that that you can do all the time

00:03:01.320 --> 00:03:07.320
But on the other hand you you have something that continues to evolve and grow without like you can keep

00:03:07.320 --> 00:03:09.320
The technical depth pretty low

00:03:09.320 --> 00:03:13.320
Now there's a third option which is to kind of say

00:03:13.320 --> 00:03:17.320
Goodbye code leave it behind start on a new adventure

00:03:17.320 --> 00:03:21.320
And

00:03:21.320 --> 00:03:28.320
For plumber I have decided the last thing so I'm excited to share with you that plumber 2 is a new package that we have

00:03:28.320 --> 00:03:30.320
Created which will

00:03:30.320 --> 00:03:34.320
Replace plumber in some sense and the rest of the talk

00:03:34.320 --> 00:03:39.320
Will basically be about me convincing you that that's a fantastic thing

00:03:39.320 --> 00:03:45.320
So what is plumber 2 well it's a it's a complete rewrite of plumber

00:03:45.320 --> 00:03:49.320
There is basically no overlap in the code base between the two

00:03:49.320 --> 00:03:54.320
Now just because it's a complete rewrite doesn't mean that it is complete new in the sense

00:03:54.320 --> 00:03:56.320
It is built on a lot of battle tested technology

00:03:56.320 --> 00:04:01.320
So it is built on top of things that have almost been around as long as plumber

00:04:01.320 --> 00:04:06.320
But the code inside the plumber 2 packages is all brand new

00:04:06.320 --> 00:04:09.320
Now don't worry if you're used to using plumber

00:04:09.320 --> 00:04:13.320
It doesn't mean that you have to go out and learn a completely new concept

00:04:13.320 --> 00:04:19.320
It will feel very familiar if you're already using plumber if you have never heard of plumber or have never used plumber

00:04:19.320 --> 00:04:27.320
I can just say that it's a it's a framework that is very easy to get into and plumber 2 kind of adapts that idea

00:04:27.320 --> 00:04:29.320
That being said it contains some breaking changes

00:04:29.320 --> 00:04:35.320
So you cannot just take your plumber applications and just like blindly port them over to plumber 2

00:04:35.320 --> 00:04:36.320
But it will be very easy

00:04:36.320 --> 00:04:42.320
And you can you can kind of take all of the knowledge that you have from plumber and apply a lot of it to plumber 2

00:04:42.320 --> 00:04:46.320
On the flip side then it is filled with amazing new features

00:04:46.320 --> 00:04:50.320
And I'll show some of them today

00:04:50.320 --> 00:04:53.320
But just to start a bit with the familiarity part

00:04:53.320 --> 00:04:58.320
So if you are used to looking at plumber code you will recognize this I hope

00:04:58.320 --> 00:05:03.320
So if you don't know anything about plumber it's a way of creating web servers by annotating R functions

00:05:03.320 --> 00:05:06.320
So it feels very much as writing an R function

00:05:06.320 --> 00:05:11.320
And if you're used to writing R functions and documentation you're used to writing Roxygen code

00:05:11.320 --> 00:05:14.320
And plumber 2 annotation feels very much like Roxygen code

00:05:14.320 --> 00:05:19.320
So this is this is something that you could put on top of your function

00:05:19.320 --> 00:05:25.320
And it will turn if you put it through plumber it will turn your function into like an end point for a web server

00:05:25.320 --> 00:05:28.320
And if you're used to this if you're used to doing this with plumber

00:05:28.320 --> 00:05:31.320
I hope that you can see that this feels very very similar

00:05:31.320 --> 00:05:34.320
Nothing dangerous here maybe some new things

00:05:34.320 --> 00:05:37.320
But some of it is completely the same so for instance this line

00:05:37.320 --> 00:05:43.320
Which defines that the function below this annotation will respond to people going to a URL

00:05:43.320 --> 00:05:46.320
Which is forecast slash some city

00:05:46.320 --> 00:05:51.320
In the example up here the city is Copenhagen that's where I'm from

00:05:51.320 --> 00:05:55.320
This is exactly the same as you would have in plumber so some of it is completely the same

00:05:55.320 --> 00:05:59.320
Now there are other things that are different we're in 2025 now

00:05:59.320 --> 00:06:04.320
So you can actually have multi-line comments in plumber 2 which is like crazy

00:06:04.320 --> 00:06:09.320
But why can we do this well it's because it doesn't just look like Roxygen 2

00:06:09.320 --> 00:06:11.320
It's actually powered by Roxygen 2 now

00:06:11.320 --> 00:06:16.320
Plumber had its own like engine for understanding this annotation

00:06:16.320 --> 00:06:19.320
But we don't need to reinvent the wheel

00:06:19.320 --> 00:06:23.320
So plumber 2 is now using Roxygen 2 to pass these things

00:06:23.320 --> 00:06:28.320
So if you're familiar with Roxygen 2 then everything that you write there will be understandable by plumber

00:06:28.320 --> 00:06:31.320
It also has some new tags

00:06:31.320 --> 00:06:35.320
So if you have your function you need to put some inputs into it

00:06:35.320 --> 00:06:39.320
One of them is the city that we talked about up here in the URL

00:06:39.320 --> 00:06:42.320
But there are other ways to put input into your end point

00:06:42.320 --> 00:06:45.320
And one of them is the query string of the URL

00:06:45.320 --> 00:06:49.320
Which is everything that follows this question mark

00:06:49.320 --> 00:06:53.320
And in plumber everything was kind of documented under the parent thing

00:06:53.320 --> 00:06:56.320
But they come different places from

00:06:56.320 --> 00:07:01.320
And that means that you could kind of mask your input in various ways

00:07:01.320 --> 00:07:06.320
Well no more because we now have a dedicated place for documenting

00:07:06.320 --> 00:07:09.320
And taking in query parameters

00:07:09.320 --> 00:07:13.320
We also have a dedicated way for things coming from the body of the request

00:07:13.320 --> 00:07:17.320
So new things but not new concepts I would say

00:07:17.320 --> 00:07:20.320
The last thing I just want to point out there is of course more to it

00:07:20.320 --> 00:07:24.320
Is that we have much richer way of documenting both the import type

00:07:24.320 --> 00:07:27.320
And the output type of the function

00:07:27.320 --> 00:07:32.320
So here we say that this output of this function when it responds to a request

00:07:32.320 --> 00:07:37.320
It responds with a 200 which means in HTTP language it means everything is okay

00:07:37.320 --> 00:07:39.320
Here's what you ask for

00:07:39.320 --> 00:07:43.320
And we also document that what is returning will be an array of objects

00:07:43.320 --> 00:07:46.320
And those objects will have an element called day which is a date

00:07:46.320 --> 00:07:49.320
An element called temperature or temp which is a number

00:07:49.320 --> 00:07:52.320
And an element called rain which is a boolean

00:07:52.320 --> 00:07:54.320
And this is just the tip of the iceberg

00:07:54.320 --> 00:07:59.320
So we have really built out the whole documentation of input and output types in Plumber 2

00:07:59.320 --> 00:08:02.320
So you can do even more

00:08:02.320 --> 00:08:04.320
So that's a bit about familiarity

00:08:04.320 --> 00:08:07.320
I hope I have convinced you that it doesn't look completely foreign

00:08:07.320 --> 00:08:09.320
But there are some new things in there

00:08:09.320 --> 00:08:11.320
So what about the features?

00:08:11.320 --> 00:08:14.320
Well this is the exciting part of everything, right?

00:08:14.320 --> 00:08:17.320
And this is where I kind of convince you that this is a good thing

00:08:17.320 --> 00:08:20.320
The first thing I want to talk about is asynchronicity

00:08:20.320 --> 00:08:26.320
Now asynchronicity for a web server is potentially important, potentially irrelevant

00:08:26.320 --> 00:08:31.320
But if you have a function that takes just a bit of time to compute

00:08:31.320 --> 00:08:36.320
You will end up blocking all the other requests that comes in while this is computing

00:08:36.320 --> 00:08:39.320
Because R is single-threaded

00:08:39.320 --> 00:08:42.320
This is not a problem if you only have one user

00:08:42.320 --> 00:08:46.320
But if you have like maybe 100 users that are constantly pinging to you or even more

00:08:46.320 --> 00:08:50.320
Then it can be a problem because everyone else has to wait for you to finish the computations

00:08:50.320 --> 00:08:52.320
This is where asynchronicity comes in

00:08:52.320 --> 00:08:54.320
You can send off the computations to another server

00:08:54.320 --> 00:08:58.320
And then pick it up once it's done and then send it back to the user while you're handling all the stuff

00:08:58.320 --> 00:09:00.320
It's not that Plumber couldn't do this

00:09:00.320 --> 00:09:04.320
If you returned a promise in a Plumber endpoint

00:09:04.320 --> 00:09:06.320
Then it could actually do the same thing

00:09:06.320 --> 00:09:08.320
But we have built this out in Plumber 2

00:09:08.320 --> 00:09:13.320
So that we can automatically convert your endpoints into asynchronous functions

00:09:13.320 --> 00:09:18.320
They are built on Mirai which is one of the newest and best packages

00:09:18.320 --> 00:09:20.320
For doing asynchronous computations in R

00:09:20.320 --> 00:09:22.320
But it is extensible as well

00:09:22.320 --> 00:09:25.320
So if you have your pet asynchronous package that you want to use instead

00:09:25.320 --> 00:09:28.320
You can actually just create a new plugin for Plumber 2

00:09:28.320 --> 00:09:32.320
To use that for asynchronous computations

00:09:32.320 --> 00:09:36.320
And as well it allows you to chain computations

00:09:36.320 --> 00:09:39.320
So usually when you have some sort of asynchronous computation

00:09:39.320 --> 00:09:43.320
You want to pick it up and you might want to do something on the mainframe in the end

00:09:43.320 --> 00:09:45.320
And you can do this with Plumber 2 with easy tagging

00:09:45.320 --> 00:09:47.320
And I'm going to show you how

00:09:47.320 --> 00:09:50.320
So how do you turn something into an asynchronous function?

00:09:50.320 --> 00:09:53.320
Well use the async tag and this is all it takes

00:09:53.320 --> 00:09:56.320
So if you pass this into Plumber 2

00:09:56.320 --> 00:09:59.320
Then Plumber 2 will take care of converting this function into an asynchronous execution

00:09:59.320 --> 00:10:02.320
And take care of all of it for you basically

00:10:02.320 --> 00:10:06.320
Now if you want to do something after this computation has done

00:10:06.320 --> 00:10:10.320
You can use the then tag following this tag

00:10:10.320 --> 00:10:13.320
And then do whatever you want to do on the mainframe before

00:10:13.320 --> 00:10:17.320
Or main thread before returning results to the request

00:10:18.320 --> 00:10:20.320
So that's async

00:10:20.320 --> 00:10:24.320
Another shiny new feature in Plumber 2 is that it supports running shiny

00:10:24.320 --> 00:10:27.320
So that should be like a meme around

00:10:27.320 --> 00:10:30.320
I put shiny in your Plumber 2

00:10:30.320 --> 00:10:33.320
You don't have to shiny on your shiny or something like that

00:10:33.320 --> 00:10:36.320
Basically what it means is that you can now launch

00:10:36.320 --> 00:10:40.320
And serve one or more shiny app as part of your Plumber 2 application

00:10:40.320 --> 00:10:43.320
Each app will run in a separate process

00:10:43.320 --> 00:10:46.320
Plumber 2 will take care of launching them

00:10:46.320 --> 00:10:49.320
And take care of tearing them down once Plumber 2 stops

00:10:49.320 --> 00:10:53.320
This is actually a subset of a more general functionality

00:10:53.320 --> 00:10:56.320
That is in Plumber 2 which is something called a reverse proxy

00:10:56.320 --> 00:10:59.320
And what this basically means is that

00:10:59.320 --> 00:11:02.320
Well you might have something that is not shiny that you want to serve through Plumber 2

00:11:02.320 --> 00:11:05.320
Well you can do that because a reverse proxy is simply a communication layer

00:11:05.320 --> 00:11:09.320
Between your front end and something else on the back end

00:11:09.320 --> 00:11:12.320
But shiny is kind of a first level citizen

00:11:12.320 --> 00:11:15.320
Because we can launch them and tear them down as we want to do

00:11:15.320 --> 00:11:18.320
How does this look? Well, surprisingly simple

00:11:18.320 --> 00:11:22.320
There's a shiny sack and you can point it to where you want to serve it from

00:11:22.320 --> 00:11:27.320
Here we have two different shiny apps that we serve from two different paths

00:11:27.320 --> 00:11:31.320
One is app slash app one and the other is slash app two

00:11:31.320 --> 00:11:34.320
So pretty simple to get going

00:11:34.320 --> 00:11:40.320
Now you don't have to serve them from a particular sub-path of your application

00:11:40.320 --> 00:11:42.320
You can also just serve it from the root

00:11:42.320 --> 00:11:45.320
Now you may think why would i even want to do that?

00:11:45.320 --> 00:11:47.320
That's just the same as launching a shiny app

00:11:47.320 --> 00:11:51.320
But you might want to do this because there's also another tag that says accept

00:11:51.320 --> 00:11:55.320
So you can serve shiny from the root

00:11:55.320 --> 00:12:01.320
But then have the rest of your api application being served from a sub-path of your url

00:12:01.320 --> 00:12:06.320
So when people visit the root of your page

00:12:06.320 --> 00:12:09.320
They're served with a shiny app

00:12:09.320 --> 00:12:15.320
But they can still interact with it with an api from a sub-path

00:12:15.320 --> 00:12:17.320
So how would you do that?

00:12:17.320 --> 00:12:20.320
Well, you'll just have a second file that you mount on a different sub-root

00:12:20.320 --> 00:12:26.320
And there you'll have all the api logic that you're used to have from a plumber

00:12:26.320 --> 00:12:28.320
There's also support for quarto

00:12:28.320 --> 00:12:33.320
So if you want to serve quarto from plumber, that's now possible

00:12:33.320 --> 00:12:38.320
If you have parameterized reports in quarto or rmarkdown

00:12:38.320 --> 00:12:43.320
These can be accessed by using the query parameters in the url

00:12:43.320 --> 00:12:46.320
Those will be funneled into the parameters in your report

00:12:46.320 --> 00:12:49.320
You can also have support for multiple outputs

00:12:49.320 --> 00:12:54.320
So if you have a report and you want to serve both a pdf and an html version of it

00:12:54.320 --> 00:13:02.320
You can just add those extensions to the path that you're querying from

00:13:02.320 --> 00:13:05.320
Or you can use a content type header to do that

00:13:05.320 --> 00:13:06.320
And it has built-in caching

00:13:06.320 --> 00:13:12.320
So it's not going to rebuild the report every time that the user is asking for it

00:13:12.320 --> 00:13:13.320
How does that look?

00:13:13.320 --> 00:13:15.320
Well, kind of like how shiny was looking

00:13:15.320 --> 00:13:18.320
So we just have a new tag called report

00:13:18.320 --> 00:13:22.320
And we're just directing it to the path where we want to serve the report from

00:13:22.320 --> 00:13:25.320
And then underneath it all, where we'd usually have an endpoint logic

00:13:25.320 --> 00:13:28.320
We'll just point to the path of the file that we want to serve

00:13:28.320 --> 00:13:32.320
And Plumber 2 takes care of all that for you

00:13:32.320 --> 00:13:35.320
Last feature that I'm going to talk about is security

00:13:35.320 --> 00:13:40.320
Now, security is quite important when it comes to web technologies

00:13:40.320 --> 00:13:44.320
It's important if you're just serving Plumber inside your own organization

00:13:44.320 --> 00:13:50.320
It is even more important if you're trying to communicate with the rest of the world

00:13:50.320 --> 00:13:54.320
And I would say that Plumber can do better in that regard

00:13:54.320 --> 00:13:57.320
And that is why Plumber 2 is doing better in that regard

00:13:57.320 --> 00:14:02.320
So Plumber 2 is coming with a bunch of plugins that you can add to your

00:14:02.320 --> 00:14:06.320
Easily add to your web server

00:14:06.320 --> 00:14:10.320
One of them is just a matter of setting best practice headers

00:14:10.320 --> 00:14:11.320
This is not like rocket science

00:14:11.320 --> 00:14:16.320
But a lot of people do not know about what all of the headers in a response should be

00:14:16.320 --> 00:14:18.320
To confine with best practices

00:14:18.320 --> 00:14:22.320
And we now take their hands and give them good defaults

00:14:22.320 --> 00:14:28.320
There's also, I think this is one of the most requested things in the Plumber github page

00:14:28.320 --> 00:14:30.320
Is something like how do I use course

00:14:30.320 --> 00:14:33.320
And if you don't know about course, I will show you in a minute

00:14:33.320 --> 00:14:36.320
And there's also something called resource isolation policies

00:14:36.320 --> 00:14:39.320
Which is another thing that we now support

00:14:39.320 --> 00:14:42.320
So going back to this example that I had with familiarity

00:14:42.320 --> 00:14:44.320
This is just the same code

00:14:44.320 --> 00:14:48.320
Consider that we have this weather forecasting service

00:14:48.320 --> 00:14:51.320
And we are running that from an api and serving it out to the world

00:14:51.320 --> 00:14:53.320
And then I have another web page

00:14:53.320 --> 00:14:54.320
I want to use this

00:14:54.320 --> 00:14:56.320
So I have a web page and some javascript

00:14:56.320 --> 00:15:01.320
And that javascript is then querying my other api

00:15:01.320 --> 00:15:03.320
Now this will not work out of the box

00:15:03.320 --> 00:15:07.320
Because the web has evolved to try to be more secure

00:15:07.320 --> 00:15:12.320
So that web pages cannot just from javascript ask other web pages for stuff

00:15:12.320 --> 00:15:15.320
This is something called cross origin resource sharing

00:15:15.320 --> 00:15:17.320
This is something that you have to turn on

00:15:17.320 --> 00:15:23.320
And say, well, I want the rest of the world to be able to kind of call what I provide

00:15:23.320 --> 00:15:26.320
Now how do I turn this on in Plumber 2?

00:15:26.320 --> 00:15:29.320
Well, surprisingly enough, it's pretty simple

00:15:29.320 --> 00:15:30.320
So we have the course tag

00:15:30.320 --> 00:15:32.320
And we just say, well, I have this web page

00:15:32.320 --> 00:15:33.320
My trusted friend

00:15:33.320 --> 00:15:38.320
I really want to interact with this other api I have

00:15:38.320 --> 00:15:43.320
And we now turn it on and everything works perfectly

00:15:43.320 --> 00:15:44.320
And then there's the rest

00:15:44.320 --> 00:15:46.320
Because there are a lot of features in this

00:15:46.320 --> 00:15:48.320
I don't have time to talk about all of it

00:15:48.320 --> 00:15:49.320
So this is just a little taster

00:15:49.320 --> 00:15:54.320
I hope I've gotten you a bit excited about what it can do

00:15:54.320 --> 00:15:56.320
So that was a bit about the features

00:15:56.320 --> 00:15:58.320
What about the future?

00:15:58.320 --> 00:16:03.320
Well, I am happy to announce that Plumber 2 is available on Crayon today

00:16:03.320 --> 00:16:08.320
Or I would have been happy to announce that if that was the fact

00:16:08.320 --> 00:16:12.320
The truth is that Plumber 2 is in the hands of Crayon today

00:16:12.320 --> 00:16:17.320
So that means that it is probably available on Crayon within a week or so

00:16:17.320 --> 00:16:20.320
It is very hard to time these things

00:16:20.320 --> 00:16:23.320
Please use it if you have anything to use it for

00:16:23.320 --> 00:16:27.320
If you don't have anything to use it for, then just, like, toy with it

00:16:27.320 --> 00:16:28.320
Have fun with it

00:16:28.320 --> 00:16:29.320
Please report any issues

00:16:29.320 --> 00:16:31.320
Please report anything that you feel is missing

00:16:31.320 --> 00:16:32.320
Any good ideas

00:16:32.320 --> 00:16:34.320
I'll be happy to add them to it

00:16:34.320 --> 00:16:37.320
Because the code is now much easier to add stuff to

00:16:37.320 --> 00:16:39.320
But also please be mindful of the novelty

00:16:39.320 --> 00:16:40.320
I'm just saying this

00:16:40.320 --> 00:16:43.320
If I got you excited, please don't run home

00:16:43.320 --> 00:16:47.320
And then, like, rewrite all the business logic of your operation in Plumber 2

00:16:47.320 --> 00:16:49.320
And then see it crash horribly

00:16:49.320 --> 00:16:51.320
It's not that I don't trust my code

00:16:51.320 --> 00:16:53.320
But it's not been battle-tested yet, right?

00:16:53.320 --> 00:16:59.320
So start out small and then grow it into your organization

00:16:59.320 --> 00:17:00.320
What about Plumber?

00:17:00.320 --> 00:17:02.320
Well, don't worry

00:17:02.320 --> 00:17:03.320
It will stay on Crayon

00:17:03.320 --> 00:17:05.319
It is now superseded by Plumber 2

00:17:05.319 --> 00:17:07.319
So it will not receive any new features

00:17:07.319 --> 00:17:12.319
If you have any requests for features, we will say, well, have a go at Plumber 2 instead

00:17:12.319 --> 00:17:13.319
But it will stay there

00:17:13.319 --> 00:17:17.319
And that means that your current APIs will continue to work as before

00:17:17.319 --> 00:17:20.319
So you are in no rush to update your packages

00:17:20.319 --> 00:17:22.319
You can just continue before

00:17:22.319 --> 00:17:28.319
And then, of course, gradually, I would advise you to move over to Plumber 2

00:17:28.319 --> 00:17:30.319
But in your own pace

00:17:30.319 --> 00:17:33.319
You can read much more about Plumber 2 at this URL

00:17:33.319 --> 00:17:36.319
And otherwise, I would just say, thank you so much for your attention

00:17:36.319 --> 00:17:40.319
I hope you will have fun writing APIs

00:17:47.319 --> 00:17:48.319
Testing

00:17:48.319 --> 00:17:49.319
Okay

00:17:52.319 --> 00:17:55.319
For now, just for these questions back and forth to you

